In C++, 2D arrays are stored in **row-major** order, meaning that the elements of the array are stored row by row in memory. When iterating over the array, the row-major order accesses all elements of a row first before moving to the next row. 

On the other hand, **column-major** order accesses elements column by column, which is not the default in C++.

